## What is psychographics? [Anchor link for: h what is psychographics](https://cxl.com/blog/psychographics/\#h-what-is-psychographics)

**Psychographics** is the psychological study of consumers and their attitudes, interests, personality, values, opinions, and lifestyles.

Psychographics are incredibly valuable for marketing, but they also have use cases in opinion research, prediction, and broader social research.

Psychographics deal primarily with what are known as [IAO variables](https://instapage.com/blog/psychographic-segmentation/)—interests, activities, and opinions. They attempt to identify the beliefs and emotions of an audience, not just their age and gender.

![psychographic market segmentation](https://lh7-rt.googleusercontent.com/docsz/AD_4nXetqzfF_Hn1ctuuR-P30CvsmjZ-m_QFhvSjeC4wHbcpySKqP8TDPmOJ9R-t6CGr3SIKR664Ods0GTSkmMyz0ffgrCiWj9iZxxZP1gvHDXDQJ8WL0qwFc8WF_xHY2eoeSYXcIXaSFqwIzWOVVgDv7i-HJKMs?key=MzPB31m-86_wpL6_i-qlig)

[(Image source)](https://www.griffith.edu.au/griffith-business-school/social-marketing-griffith/resources/segmentation)

### The difference between psychographics and demographics

**In contrast to psychographic data that covers opinions and interests, demographic data relates to the structure of a population—factors like age, race, sex, and income.**

Demographics are, of course, used in a broad variety of areas, including education, government, business, etc., for things like policy development and economic research.

Even at a micro level, it’s nice to know your audience’s demographics and which demographics make the best customers for your business—especially when you’re ramping up ad spend.

![demographic factors vs psychographics factors](https://lh7-rt.googleusercontent.com/docsz/AD_4nXcY302lFlSheLo1fA9iijyzFHQ8Lii-FiJULXL5aLj7uysdQfr0e2iIGBomf8ajUrGqdPTfBfl1-EjgRCwvSnRZEgibniYxazug_52OzMo4KXzXdwsp2A9J38UP1-Wm7vRW6HpaFMHAmtv_Et9Cpcf28N7X?key=MzPB31m-86_wpL6_i-qlig)

[(Image source)](https://6sense.com/blog/demystifying-psychographics/)

Neither data types should stand alone. You can analyze psychographic data in relation to demographic, geographic, or [behavioral data](https://cxl.com/blog/behavioral-personas/), in addition to firmographic data, which is especially important for [account-based marketing](https://cxl.com/institute/online-course/account-based-marketing/).

### Why psychographics are important

What’s the big benefit of psychographics for marketing (other than sounding cool)?

Essentially, if you know _how_ people choose and compare products in your category, you know how to structure and prioritize content:

- If you know their deepest held beliefs, you can align your marketing messaging more closely.
- If you know what they _don’t_ care about, you can dismiss those messages and pull them from your site.
- If you know what they read, you know where to reach them.
- And on and on.

Psychographics tell you _why_ people buy. They help you build robust [user personas](https://cxl.com/blog/user-personas/).

They help you craft the right message and put it in the right place. They’re less objective and clean, but—for a marketer—they’re super useful.

## 3 types of psychographics [Anchor link for: h 3 types of psychographics](https://cxl.com/blog/psychographics/\#h-3-types-of-psychographics)

The main types of psychographics are interests, activities, and opinions.

You can split that into subcategories as well. (Attitudes are slightly different than opinions; lifestyle and behavior are slightly different than activities).

However, let’s stick to the main three.

### **1\. Interests**

**Interests are inclinations and affinities.**

You can find some basic interests and affinities in your Google Analytics data.

I’ll be honest, I really haven’t done much with Google Analytics’ reported interest data (at least in terms of [conversion optimization](https://cxl.com/conversion-optimization//)), though there are ways to use this data.

For instance, you can see conversion rates and ecommerce data based on affinity category:

![screenshot of conversion rates and ecommerce data based on affinity category](https://lh7-rt.googleusercontent.com/docsz/AD_4nXdtklzQRm_y0dI8HMIu0bQVTraxmvqWU-Ey3rx2NJEuaf1ceUuTNERRCsfxLkvRMIznaxpB9uy6fePePt_16rd6K-A1yBmiwDUfnqq5Js7KhojF4wLV0FKKeOnuiBepkKCmCNQKHivIZq_T0E5iOhOf34oB?key=MzPB31m-86_wpL6_i-qlig)

[(Image Source)](https://blog.crobox.com/article/psychographic-marketing#:~:text=Psychographic%20marketing%20helps%20marketers%20penetrate,for%20a%20data%2Ddriven%20approach.)

This data, I suppose, could provide a little bit of insight into your best customers. Realistically, however, I don’t think this is the most valuable Google Analytics data.

One brand that leverages its customers’ interests is Johnny Walker.  When Game of Thrones was at its peak they released “White Walker.” Just brilliant.

![screenshot of Johnnie Walker Game of Thrones "White Walker" campaign](https://lh7-rt.googleusercontent.com/docsz/AD_4nXcnzRvCiu8NrW4aWuZYTz5QiDnD1-yDdCVq3D5RHoLIXDWB0SKI6mn0SQR1g-xEo7P9R7olMIXyB9FAC6Bi1rOJ42AjsJU5sokQ8Td8JSWR_vcOrhw70KHYXzz8Ndf31A5G0xNsGgh6mhCz0o4kTl9kE7Y?key=MzPB31m-86_wpL6_i-qlig)

[(Image Source)](https://blog.crobox.com/article/psychographic-segmentation)

### **2\. Activities**

**Activities are what people do**—things like skiing, reading, fishing, weightlifting.

Sometimes this data is irrelevant. For instance, if you sell a SaaS product, you can’t immediately do anything with the fact that some of your customers like to fish.

But if you ask the right questions—good, [open-ended questions](https://cxl.com/blog/open-ended-questions/) that let you know your customer better—you can learn how customers spend their day, what they care about, where they hang out, and what they align with.

A simple question like, “Other than work and sleep, how do you spend your time?” can elicit great responses.

Starbucks uses its customers’ favorite hobbies, like reading and baking, to connect with its audience, especially those that go with a good cup of coffee.

![screenshot of Starbucks IG post using hobbies to connect to customers](https://lh7-rt.googleusercontent.com/docsz/AD_4nXftBFTeV4WE-wD2whX3VqMCjj7j9Gf9IeytF1az3012DcF4mqM_zjMdvjONHXRMBQcf-3OHnwkIwJSaOMdyTEAhghxIW8-wBNJ4xWyqFO4AChvJpie99yHGZP_vCCigzbFkDgMkUsMLMuIhVCWsL6ocxLI?key=MzPB31m-86_wpL6_i-qlig)

[(Image Source)](https://www.instagram.com/p/C9m8km3SPXM/?img_index=1)

You can use trends in activity psychographics to better target your customer via ads, write better content that uses metaphors and references from their activities, or cater events and even selling to their preferences.

### **3\. Opinions**

**Everyone has opinions.** When people have similar opinions, they tend to form tribes (which is when [Cialdini’s Unity principle](https://cxl.com/blog/cialdini-unity/) comes into play).

Have you noticed an increase in brands displaying their opinions and values? When Super Bowl commercials have been controversial, it was usually because they ventured to share an opinion of the world.

Opinions and attitudes are an untapped opportunity for brands. Instead of repeated exposure via display ads, introducing values to your brand can help people know where to stand in relation to your company.

Think of a brand like [Patagonia](http://www.patagonia.com/environmentalism.html). You know what they stand for.

![screenshot of Patagonia's displaying its brand opinions and values](https://lh7-rt.googleusercontent.com/docsz/AD_4nXdpP-NKpk7Y6ZegMZVHFfcux0xivIA2PogqRjiv_X8HajOaaiPAVFtHYdSIabK1rj0c2JOqOoNhxkXERY8XsM4IGP0BPmmb8WQTJPoFo5417xDp5_9iLJF4Uf8zMzbZqGHDZorME4Ep9PyXOvlrVq8JdG7K?key=MzPB31m-86_wpL6_i-qlig)

This is one of the most important areas in psychographics. Read more on how brands can create shared value in [this great article](https://thestrategystory.com/blog/creating-shared-value-explained-with-examples/).

## Psychographic research methods [Anchor link for: h psychographic research methods](https://cxl.com/blog/psychographics/\#h-psychographic-research-methods)

How do you learn about the psychographics of your target market? There are many ways, some easy and passive, others rigorous and active.

[In an excellent HBR article](https://hbr.org/2016/03/psychographics-are-just-as-important-for-marketers-as-demographics), Alexandra Samuel outlines how technology has enabled us to collect psychographic data more easily.

She includes online communities, social media analytics (including [sentiment analysis](http://nlp.stanford.edu/sentiment/)), and [social media listening](https://cxl.com/blog/social-media-market-research/) in this list:

_Online customer communities let you ask about a range of consumer attitudes: my own data on 10,000 North American parents was gathered from two such communities._

_Social media analytics lets you identify trends in interests and attitudes, and even use sentiment analysis to help dig a little more deeply into psychographic attitudes._

_Social media monitoring is hugely valuable, too, since the organic conversations that emerge online may help you spot emerging issues or psychographic clusters.”_

Even [Google Analytics](https://cxl.com/blog/google-analytics-segmentation/) gives you _some_ data on your customers’ affinities and interests, as mentioned above. But, the best way is through rigorous [user persona research](https://cxl.com/blog/creating-customer-personas-using-data-driven-research/), [customer interviews](https://cxl.com/blog/customer-interviews/), and [customer surveys](https://cxl.com/blog/customer-surveys/).

In fact, the best user personas contain demographic, psychographic, firmographic, and behavioral data. For example, here’s a customer profile:

Demographic:

- Male;
- Aged 24–35;
- Single, no children;
- Household income $75k–125k;
- Works in technology.

![screenshot of Adobe's customer survey](https://lh7-rt.googleusercontent.com/docsz/AD_4nXd-WrNEsvmK-f0BMRywAggRYniKtRlSv2MzmsCV8s1KYZ1hM0_m-aqHSDjsjxtFRBs6aeWGRP3bkz2ccLp5z64GTLNVKLIEfTJkCDIzaJ7Ol-7D6Xo6gU9eYBh6f296bLXmXIKnDxp6ziONUuVxC1x53TJz?key=MzPB31m-86_wpL6_i-qlig)

[(Image Source)](https://blog.hubspot.com/service/questionnaire#questionnaireexamples)

Psychographic:

- Does yoga on the weekends;
- Believes we need to do something about climate change;
- Hobby photographer.

![screenshot of surveymonkey's survey](https://lh7-rt.googleusercontent.com/docsz/AD_4nXd-AoPNJKz12Os38bUN8EEOWZZW9pPvp7E-lLRT4KZotBaiW4-WdY625cp1rRhVIvvHpsRbmfM6npIWLJjy4vGJnW-GOPgi65HgIKBg5q45iGTpVGxtulgFChbwf1CfWgQQSNpv3hMgdizfueUoKHj6Art3?key=MzPB31m-86_wpL6_i-qlig)

[(Image Source)](https://blog.hubspot.com/service/questionnaire#questionnaireexamples)

Behavioral:

- Shops at organic grocery stores;
- Spends a lot of money on travel;
- Volunteers at a climate-change organization;
- Logs into our app on a daily basis.

![tracking webshop behavioral data](https://lh7-rt.googleusercontent.com/docsz/AD_4nXep_asgyXK1QBLmfIPZrEXkd8tAp1C56QdNG2E5Y3pXx5X-K6FORpSOEcIGMri7RfM0HfWF-8SkhPsFWAUTN8pkLb-NDo354AuqXuq_bUPM1YhO-4hGz07Lck3zrSZ25gPj0ec4DniBxjICZsbAQmDCOJiC?key=MzPB31m-86_wpL6_i-qlig)

[(Image Source)](https://blog.crobox.com/article/psychographic-marketing#:~:text=Psychographic%20marketing%20helps%20marketers%20penetrate,for%20a%20data%2Ddriven%20approach.)

With just one of the above categories, you can see how the picture is less rounded. (That’s my guess for a [Headspace](https://www.headspace.com/) persona, by the way.)

## How to use psychographics in your marketing: an example [Anchor link for: h how to use psychographics in your marketing an example](https://cxl.com/blog/psychographics/\#h-how-to-use-psychographics-in-your-marketing-an-example)

The problem with psychographics, at least historically, is that people have deemed the data to be less actionable (and harder to collect) than demographic data.

However, as Samuel explains, the internet has made psychographics more actionable and easier to access.

Take a user persona based on a mix of demographic and psychographic data. Sure, you want to know their general age range, salary range, and geolocation. Those things make it easier to target your customers on a granular level.

But psychographics— _why_ they make decisions—help you with messaging, [persuasion](https://cxl.com/blog/emotional-persuasion-guide/), and creative.

Here’s Samuel again:

_Yes, families with different incomes, or with younger and older kids, make somewhat different technology purchases. But their reasons for purchasing are much more closely tied to parent psychographics._

_Parents who trust their kids to make their own tech decisions (whom I call “enablers”) tend to evaluate their tech purchases in terms of fun and entertainment value._

_Parents who focus on minimizing screen time (“limiters”) gravitate towards software and devices that support their kids’ literacy, math, and academic skills._

_Parents who actively guide and encourage their kids’ technology use typically look for purchases that offer a balance of fun and educational value, and that offer ways to engage and play as a family._

_When you understand these kinds of psychographic differences, online marketing tools will make your insight actionable in a way that was nearly impossible before the heyday of Google, Facebook, and Twitter._

With psychographic data, it’s much easier to [design landing pages](https://cxl.com/blog/landing-page-optimization/) for key personas. When you’re creating messages and designs for a specific person, you’re doing less guesswork than what you might if you followed typical [best practices](https://cxl.com/blog/best-practice-and-optimisation-experts/).

[(Image Source)](https://dribbble.com/shots/1085739-MailChimp-Persona-Project)

Psychographics don’t just help with messaging and creative; they also help with keyword targeting. Not only can you **build the right message**, but you can also use psychographic targeting to put it in the right place in front of the right people.

As Samuel put it:

_Using psychographics allows you to do smarter keyword targeting – for example, targeting one message about your programming game to parents who are searching for “kids programming” and another message to parents who are searching for “kids videogames fun.”_

_Once you know the key differences in what your customers care about, you can target Facebook ads to parents who’ve liked specific pages or identified particular interests; you can figure out the hashtags that different psychographic groups use on Twitter, and target different tweets (or even different accounts) to those groups._

Want to see something hilarious? [Check out your ad preferences on Facebook.](https://www.facebook.com/ads/preferences) It shows you exactly what Facebook thinks you’re into (and alludes to why you see some of the ads you do) and all kinds of segmentation that applies to your profile.

Some of it can be pretty accurate. For instance, the news and entertainment section is semi-close for me:

![Screenshot of Facebook user interests](https://lh7-rt.googleusercontent.com/docsz/AD_4nXcqvIQRYBr7DWNntXANDz4HFd0kw3pmYjQk9FqbM47fSGRS5w8BvUOBoJ5ca2BqKki_LVH6PfFrEh54jY8xW1_jyIWIERmsf23xHrXwI820LuOqwhNW-027866CpXIDdVaseg5nGxrZG1tHoxy5PtnVKaMx?key=MzPB31m-86_wpL6_i-qlig)

And I’m a big fan of my “hobbies” section, if only because it contains four dog-related categories and a fox (for some reason):

![Screenshot of Facebook user interests](<Base64-Image-Removed>)

But, sometimes, Facebook gets weird. It thinks that my “lifestyle and culture” category should include The Conservative Party of Canada, Communism, Meme, and Citrus:

![Screenshot of Facebook user interests](<Base64-Image-Removed>)

Anyway, brands are collecting this data about you, and ad platforms are making that data useful to ad buyers. You can target people at an incredibly granular level of behavioral, demographic, and psychographic data.

Still, we have a long way to go with psychographic targeting, for a variety of technical and methodological reasons, even as we’re getting better. That’s why I’m targeted by Chubbies and The Economist.

Facebook, for the most part, knows what I’m into:

![screenshots of Facebook sponsored ads or suggested posts (Chubbies) based on user interests](<Base64-Image-Removed>)

## Conclusion [Anchor link for: h conclusion](https://cxl.com/blog/psychographics/\#h-conclusion)

Psychographics are important—not just for messaging strategy and emotional targeting in your ads and on your site, but for _how_ and _where_ you acquire customers.

It’s increasingly easy to get good psychographic data and put it to use through advanced ad targeting and even [on-site personalization](https://cxl.com/blog/personalization/). It’s no longer a guessing game as to whether it works, either, given your [ability to test messaging at scale.](https://cxl.com/blog/ab-testing-tools/)

Psychographics help you know your customer. And knowing your customer better makes your marketing better. [Master the art of digital psychology and persuasion](https://cxl.com/institute/programs/digital-psychology-persuasion-training/) and connect with your audience in a more meaningful and effective way.

